The purpose of this study is to evaluate existing safety performance and to identify potential
countermeasures to reduce congestion and traffic crashes at the intersection of State Route 283 (Lake
Shore Boulevard) and State Route 306 (Reynolds Road) the city of Mentor, Ohio. This section of State
Route 283 from mile point 8.40 to to 8.70 is ranked 42 on the ODOT 2011 Urban Non-Freeway Peak
A review of crash data provided by the Ohio Department of Transportation (ODOT) yielded a total of 106
reported crashes within the study area during a 3-year period between 2009 and 2011. Of the total
reported crashes, 28.3 percent resulted in injury (no fatalities), which is higher than the statewide average
of 25.7 percent for injury crashes on state route, non-freeway locations during the same period.
The following crash types and conditions are over represented on the study corridor compared to
statewide averages (shown in parenthesis). Note the statewide crash averages are based on 2007-2011
data whereas the project data encompasses years 2009 to 2011.

State Route 283 (Lake Shore Boulevard) is an east-west route that parallels State Route 2 (SR-2) and I-90,
in Mentor, Ohio. Reynolds Road runs north-south and is designated as State Route 306 only south of the
intersection as State Route 306 ends at the intersection. Both State Routes are classified as minor urban
arterials. Land uses along State Routes 283 and 306 are generally suburban residential, although
neighborhood commercial land uses are located in the four quadrants of the intersection. A project
location map is provided in Figure 1.
Lake Shore Boulevard intersects Reynolds Road at a 4 leg signalized intersection. Lake Shore Boulevard
and the north leg of Reynolds Road are both 2-lane roadway segments. Lake Shore Boulevard widens to
a 3-lane section between Campbell Road and Reynolds Road. Bike lanes also exist on Lake Shore
Boulevard. Reynolds Road south of Lake Shore Boulevard is a 4-lane undivided roadway approaching the
intersection and widens to 5-lanes, providing a dedicated left, through and right turn lanes, as well as two
Lake Shore Boulevard intersects the south leg of Reynolds Road at a slight skew of approximately 75
degrees. The intersection skew is within acceptable limits outlined in the ODOT L&D manual. The skew
of the intersection, however, increases the complexity of the driving task with the addition of an angle
point between the northbound and southbound approaches of Reynolds Road. The intersection
misalignment of Reynolds Road in conjunction with the intersection skew causes a negative offset of the
opposing left turn movements on Reynolds Road. Figure 2 shows how the misalignment impacts traffic
Northbound left turn movement. The northbound left turn lane is shifted about 6 feet to the right
of the preferred position to see opposing southbound through traffic.
Northbound through movement. The angle point of the intersection requires a full lane transition
across the intersection to avoid the curb on the northeast quadrant.
Southbound left turn movement. The southbound left turn lane is shifted about 8 feet to the left
of the preferred position to see opposing northbound through traffic.
An adjacent traffic signal is located 900 feet to the west at Campbell Road. The two traffic signals
operate as isolated intersections and are not part of a coordinated timing plan.
Overhead lighting is provided along the roadways, with cobra style lighting mounting on wood utility
poles. Street lighting at the intersection is only provided in the northeast and southwest quadrant, though
lighting exists downstream on southeast and northwest quadrants.

The Lake Shore Boulevard and Reynolds Road intersection is controlled with a traffic signal using mast
arm signal supports. Other features of the existing traffic signal include the following:
Westbound, northbound and southbound left turns are all protected-permitted movements
controlled with a 5-section head. An overlap right turn is provided for the northbound right turn.
The eastbound left turn movement on Lake Shore Boulevard is a permitted only movement.
There is no crosswalk or pedestrian signal head on the east leg of the intersection, though no
signing prohibiting the movement was identified at the intersection. Crosswalks, pedestrian
signal heads and pushbuttons are provided on all other legs.

The functional area of an intersection is defined as the area beyond the physical intersection of two
roadways. The functional area for a leg of an intersection includes two components: one upstream of the
physical area of the intersection and one downstream. The upstream (or intersection approach) includes
additional length for decision-making, maneuvering, and required vehicle storage. The downstream area
consists of a conflict overlap distance that allows a through vehicle to clear the intersection in addition to
downstream conflict points. The downstream distance is calculated to be 155 feet and is based on a
design speed of 25 MPH. The functional area of a typical intersection is shown in Figure 4.

Manual turning movement counts were conducted at the Lake Shore Boulevard and Reynolds Road
intersection on March 27, 2013 during the morning (7-9 AM), noon (12-1 PM), and evening hours (4-6
PM). This data was obtained using Miovision technology.
Additional turning movement count data was collected on May 1, 2013 as part of the safety study to
obtain 8-hour turn count data and to confirm if multi-cycle backups occurred at the signalized
intersection. No multi-cycle queues were documented at the Lake Shore Boulevard and Reynolds Road
approach. Manual count data was submitted to the NOACA for certification of design year growth rates

The following sections address each of the high frequency crash patterns identified on the corridor.
Rear end crashes, while present on all approaches, are concentrated on the eastbound approach (36 of the
total 63 rear end crashes). Review of crashes by hour of day indicates that the crashes, and specifically
rear end crashes, have a significant peak coinciding with the 3 p.m. (school peak) and 6 p.m. (commuter
peak) periods (See Figure 7). These two peak hours represented 40 of the 63 total rear end crashes.
Congestion is often a contributing factor to rear end crashes. Although field crews collecting the manual
turn count data did not observe multi-cycle backups on any of the approaches at the signalized
intersection, individual movements experience levels of service of E or worse (i.e., eastbound approach,
westbound left, and northbound left) . Capacity analysis section in Appendix E contains the detailed
Other factors that may contribute to the frequency of rear end crashes include the following:
Driver age. The majority of crashes (76 percent) involve higher risk drivers – young (16-25
years old) and/or elderly (61+ years old) drivers. Inexperienced drivers combined with drivers
having slower perception/reaction times result in a percentage of crashes within the study area
that is 2 times higher than the statewide average (76 percent vs 38 percent statewide average).
Queue lengths. Figure 3 shows that the queue length on the eastbound approach can extend to
the Campbell Road intersection. The split time for the eastbound approach is sufficient to deliver
queues of this length. Queue lengths of 800 feet however block existing driveways causing
conflict points that can contribute to rear end crashes on Lake Shore Boulevard -- trailing vehicles
cannot determine the intended direction for turning and/or slowing traffic.
FIGURE 7: FREQUENCY OF CRASHES BY TIME OF DAY
All angle crashes except one occurred at driveways and not at the signalized intersection. There are two
The Speedway access (southwest quadrant) onto Lake Shore Boulevard
Commercial access (northeast quadrant) onto Lake Shore Boulevard.
The majority of crashes at these access points involve left turning traffic from the private driveway.
These crash patterns are indicative of exiting traffic crossing a standing queue and colliding with vehicles
in an adjacent lane. In these instances, the adjacent lane is an exclusive left turn lane.
Half (5 crashes) of the left turn crashes involved the northbound left turn movement from Reynolds Road
onto Lake Shore Boulevard. A contributing factor for these crashes is the negative offset of the left
turning vehicles caused by the skew angle on Reynolds Road. Southbound left turning vehicles restrict
the sight distance of northbound left turning vehicles – the result is northbound left turning vehicles
pulling out in front of southbound through traffic.
Two bicycle crashes involving 13 year olds were also reported on Lake Shore Boulevard. One recorded
on the northern leg of Magnolia Drive, involving a vehicle exiting Magnolia Drive and a cyclist on Lake
Shore Boulevard and the other at the strip development access point 500 feet west of Reynolds Road
involving a vehicle entering the access point. These locations are in areas where queues could block the
access point, but still permit cyclists to advance in the cleared bike lane.
Modify the yellow clearance and all red clearance times per ODOT Traffic Engineering Manual and ITE
guidelines, as summarized in Appendix D. Recommended clearance intervals are based on posted speeds
of 25 mph and actual crossing distances. NCHRP Report 731 dated July 2012 confirms that the ITE
clearance interval guidelines are used by the highest percentage of state and local agencies resulting in a
total crash reduction of 8 to 14 percent – an injury reduction of 12 percent also can be expected.
The NCHRP Report 731 also recommends using a design speed of 20 MPH for left turning vehicles. This
finding is consistent with research conducted by the North Carolina Department of Transportation
published by the ITE Journal determined that the average operating speed for left turning traffic is 17
miles per hour. Clearance intervals for the protected left turn phase are based on a design speed of 20
miles per hour. This methodology helps provide adequate all-red clearance times based on operating
speeds and avoids excessively long clearance intervals (yellow + AR).
Revised pavement markings are recommended on the northbound approach to improve intersection sight
distance of left turn movements and the alignment of northbound through vehicles. Figure 8 shows a
concept plan that shifts the northbound lanes thus eliminating one of the two southbound receiving lanes.
The removal of a southbound receiving lane will not affect intersection capacity since no dual lanes feed
the southbound movement. This change will also improve the turning radius of the northbound right turn

Student education at the primary school level is proposed as a countermeasure to inform bicyclists and
pedestrian about basic road safety. The proper use of bike lanes and potential hazards at driveways and
intersections are elements of a program that would help address specific safety issues within the Lake
Shore Boulevard and Reynolds Road study area.
Student driver education at the secondary school is proposed as a countermeasure to inform young drivers
of the safety risks of distracted driving. Specific safety data can be referenced showing the percentage of
young drivers involved in crashes within the Lake Shore Boulevard and Reynolds Road study area.

The National Cooperative Highway Research Program (NCHRP) Report 731: Guidelines for Timing
Yellow and All-Red Intervals at Signalized Intersections was published July 2012. A number of
conclusions were reached as a result of the comprehensive study that is important to the safety
The Institute of Transportation Engineers (ITE) Proposed Recommended Practice for the
calculation of yellow change intervals and all-red clearance intervals is the methodology used by
the highest percentage of state and local agencies.
Drivers were documented to decelerate when turning at an intersection. The NCHRP Report 731
recommended using a design speed of 20 mile per hour for the calculation of all red timing.
Research conducted by the North Carolina Department of Transportation published by the ITE
Journal determined that the average operating speed for left turning traffic is 17 miles per hour.
Using the current ITE guidelines to calculate the duration of yellow change and red clearance
intervals has been shown to reduce total crashes between 8 and 14 percent while reducing injury
Using the current ITE guidelines to calculate the duration of yellow change and red clearance
intervals has been shown to reduce red light running occurrences between 36 and 50 percent.
Vehicular clearance times were calculated for each study area intersection based on guidelines published
in the Ohio Manual of Uniform Traffic Control Devices and the ITE Proposed Recommended Practice.

Turn lane lengths were calculated for turn lanes at the Lake Shore Blvd/Reynolds Road intersection. Lane
lengths were first calculated using guidelines specified in the Location and Design Manual Section 401 (Ohio
Department of Transportation). Lane lengths based on the ODOT’s standard criteria assume posted speed
limits and include vehicle storage and a 50 foot diverging taper. The calculated lengths were compared to the
percentile queue lengths generated by SimTraffic modeling software. A recommended length is provided
based on this comparison and available space between adjacent intersections. A summary of the lane sizing
comparison is shown in Table F1 with lane sizing calculations attached to this section.
